  "prompt": "What is the candela? What is it used for?",
  "response": "The candela is one of the seven base units in the International System of Units (SI). It is the unit of luminous intensity, which measures the amount of light emitted by a source in a particular direction. Specifically, one candela is defined as the luminous intensity of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency 540 x 10^12 hertz and has a radiant intensity of 1/683 watt per steradian in that direction. \n\nThe candela is used primarily in fields related to lighting, optics, and vision, and it helps quantify how bright a light source appears to the human eye. It is a fundamental unit for specifying how bright a light source will appear and is particularly important in applications involving lighting design, display technology, photography, and in the specification of light fixtures. \n\nFor example, the brightness of light sources such as bulbs, LEDs, and lasers is often expressed in candelas, helping consumers and manufacturers understand how much light is produced and how it should be perceived in different environments.",
